Since you asked for an alternative approach to using `MemoryStream`, you could use `Request.EnableBuffering()`, perhaps. I would suggest checking &quot;[Re-reading ASP.Net Core request bodies with EnableBuffering()][1]&quot; out over on devblogs.microsoft.com...

Essentially, your `OnMessageReceived` would look something like this:

```csharp
if (ctx.Request.Method.Equals(&quot;POST&quot;)
{
    ctx.Request.EnableBuffering();
    using (var reader = new StreamReader(ctx.Request.Body, Encoding.UTF8, true, $YOURBUFFERSIZE$, true))
    {
        var jsonBody = reader.ReadToEnd();
        var body = JsonConvert.DeserializeObject&lt;BaseRequest&gt;(jsonBody);
        if (body != null)
        {
            ctx.Token = body.Token;
            ctx.Request.Headers[&quot;Authorization&quot;] = $&quot;Bearer {body.Token}&quot;;
            ctx.Request.Body.Position = 0;
        }
    }
}
```

Frankly, this itself is not the best way to do it, but if you really want to avoid modifying anything other than your `OnMessageReceived`, I guess this method doesn&#39;t require the use of `MemoryStream`.


  [1]: https://devblogs.microsoft.com/aspnet/re-reading-asp-net-core-request-bodies-with-enablebuffering/

